<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO SPORTS ET CETERA: STANFORD WOMEN RING UP RECORD ROUT OF SDSU, 109-45 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Without much size or experience, San Diego State's women's basketball team 
posed little trouble for Stanford, the No. 3-ranked team in the NCAA. The 
Cardinal (3-0), which set one Pac 10 record and three school records, defeated 
SDSU, 109-45, Sunday in Palo Alto. 
</P>
<P>
Stanford's Katy Steding led six players in double-figure scoring with a 
career-high 27 points. Val Whiting had a career-high 19. The 64-point margin of 
victory was a Stanford record, topping a 57-point victory over Wisconsin last 
season. 
</P>
<P>
Stanford's 11 three-pointers tied a Pacific-10 single-game record. Steding had 
five of those for another school record. 
</P>
<P>
SDSU (0-6) had just player in double figures scoring -- senior guard Julie 
Evans had 16 points. 
</P>
<P>
TENNIS 
</P>
<P>
Jeff Miyamoto of San Diego defeated David Bain of Newport Beach, 6-4, 1-6, 6-3, 
to win the Boys' 16 junior championship at the J.P. Yamasaki tournament at 
Santiago Canyon Tennis Club in Orange. Deta Huber of La Jolla won the Girls' 16 
singles and doubles. 
</P>
<P>
Other winners in the second-largest junior tournament in California included, 
Jeff Young of Escondido in the Boys' 14, and San Diego's James Conda and Reggie 
Buenviaje in the Boys' 16 doubles. 
</P>
<P>
MEN'S SOCCER 
</P>
<P>
Trong Nguyen, a University of San Diego midfielder, was selected to the West 
Coast Conference first team for the second consecutive year. Two other Toreros 
-- Jason Pearson and Tom Crane were named on the second team. 
</P>
</TEXT>
