<HEADLINE>
<P>
PEOPLE'S PHARMACY: FDA AWARDS GENERIC DRUGS A 99% CLEAN BILL OF HEALTH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOE GRAEDON and DR. TERESA GRAEDON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The dust is slowly starting to settle on the generic drug scandal. The Food and 
Drug Administration has completed a preliminary survey of top-selling generic 
medications and found that 99% were fine. 
</P>
<P>
The news came as a tremendous relief for Henry. His father and grandfather both 
died of heart attacks at an early age. His own blood pressure is high and his 
cholesterol is elevated. To control these health threats, Henry takes Calan and 
Lasix for hypertension and Nicobid for cholesterol control. 
</P>
<P>
Before questions were raised about the safety and effectiveness of generic 
drugs, Henry's monthly bill was $37. But Henry got scared after reading the 
headlines, and had his pharmacist fill his prescriptions with only brand names. 
His bill soared to over $175. 
</P>
<P>
This was a hardship for Henry and his wife, but like millions of other 
Americans, he didn't want to risk his health on dubious generic drugs. Now, 
Henry should be reassured that the vast majority of generic drugs meet federal 
standards. 
</P>
<P>
Answering the question, "Are the generic drugs on the market safe and 
effective?" FDA Commissioner Dr. Frank Young recently responded, "The answer 
appears to be a qualified yes." 
</P>
<P>
The FDA's conclusion was reached after examining 30 of the most widely used 
generics, medicines like hydrochlorothiazide, prednisone, antibiotics such as 
amoxicillin, cephalexin and erythromycin, pain-relievers containing 
acetaminophen and codeine or propoxyphene, and many others. 
</P>
<P>
The tests considered whether these generic medications were indeed chemically 
identical to their brand-name counterparts; if the active ingredients were as 
strong as those in the brand-name medicines, and if the pills dissolved 
properly -- a short-cut to determining if these medicines get into the 
bloodstream as they should. 
</P>
<P>
The results show that in most cases generic drugs are as good as brand-name 
medications. Drugs that flunk the tests are being withdrawn. 
</P>
<P>
The generic drug mess was brought to light as a result of whistle-blowing from 
within the industry itself. One of the major manufacturers of generic products 
felt that FDA officials had shown favoritism to its rivals. 
</P>
<P>
Now that the feds have cracked down, physicians, pharmacists and patients 
should return to using generic drugs with confidence. The savings are too 
important to ignore. 
</P>
</TEXT>
